<span class="header1">BUSINESS & TECHNOLOGY</span>
<p>Technology is becoming more and more important in running an
office.  The occupations in this field need people who know how
business machines and equipment work. If you enjoy working with
equipment or machines, this field may be for you.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Computer and Information Systems
Manager</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/CF/43334.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Computer and Information
Systems " />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Computer and information systems managers plan,
coordinate, and direct research and facilitate the computer-related
activities of firms. They help determine both technical and business
goals in consultation with top management and make detailed plans
for the accomplishment of these goals. This requires a strong
understanding of both technology and business practices.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>A bachelor's degree usually is required for
management positions, although employers often prefer a graduate
degree, especially an MBA with technology as a core component.  Some
universities offer degrees in management information systems. These
degrees blend technical subjects with business, accounting, and
communications courses.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of computer and
information system managers was $135,800 in May 2016. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Computer Software
Engineer</span><br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Computer software engineers apply the principles
of computer science and mathematical analysis to the design,
development, testing, and evaluation of the software and systems
that make computers work.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Most employers prefer applicants who have at
least a bachelor's degree and experience with a variety of computer
systems and technologies. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of computer software
engineers was $102,280 in May 2016.
</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Computer Service
Technician</span><br /><br />
	<!-- <img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/CF/1234.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Computer Service
Technician" /> -->
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Computers are very important to our society and
will continue to be in the future. If you like knowing what makes
computers work and want to keep them running, you might become a
computer service technician. In this job, you figure out why a
computer isn't working and fix it.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Employers prefer workers who are certified or
who have training in electronics from an associate degree program,
the military, a vocational school, or an equipment manufacturer.
</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of computer service
technicians was $52,160 in May 2016.
</blockquote>

